    "result": {"data":{"challengeNode":{"challenge":{"videoId":null,"videoLocaleIds":null,"bilibiliIds":null,"title":"Task 80","description":"<section id=\"description\">\n<p>The word <code>actually</code> is used when you want to tell the real fact about something, especially if it's different from what someone thought or said. It's like saying, <code>No, this is how it really is</code>. You use <code>actually</code> to make your point stronger or to correct what someone else said.</p>\n</section>","challengeType":19,"helpCategory":"English","superBlock":"a2-english-for-developers","block":"learn-how-to-ask-and-share-about-educational-and-professional-background","fields":{"slug":"/learn/a2-english-for-developers/learn-how-to-ask-and-share-about-educational-and-professional-background/task-80","blockName":"learn-how-to-ask-and-share-about-educational-and-professional-background","tests":[]},"question":{"text":"<p>What does <code>actually</code> imply in a sentence like <code>I actually prefer working remotely</code>?</p>","answers":[{"answer":"<p>The truth is contrary to what might have been assumed or stated before</p>","feedback":null},{"answer":"<p>I never work remotely</p>","feedback":"<p><code>Actually</code> in this context is used to express a real preference.</p>"},{"answer":"<p>I always work in an office setting</p>","feedback":"<p>Using <code>actually</code> here is meant to reveal a preference for remote work, not office work.</p>"},{"answer":"<p>I don't have any work preferences</p>","feedback":"<p><code>Actually</code> suggests a specific preference, contradicting the idea of having none.</p>"}],"solution":1},"scene":null,"translationPending":false,"assignments":[],"audioPath":null}}},"pageContext":{"challengeMeta":{"blockHashSlug":"/learn/a2-english-for-developers/#learn-how-to-ask-and-share-about-educational-and-professional-background","dashedName":"task-80","certification":"a2-english-for-developers","disableLoopProtectTests":false,"disableLoopProt